# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computational-neuroscience
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Central to these models is the description of how the membrane potential (that is, the difference in electric potential between the interior and the exterior of a biological cell) across the cell membrane changes over time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In an experimental setting, stimulating neurons with an electrical current generates an action potential (or spike), that propagates down the neuron's axon.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This axon can branch out and connect to a large number of downstream neurons at sites called synapses.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] At these synapses, the spike can cause the release of neurotransmitters, which in turn can change the voltage potential of downstream neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This change can potentially lead to even more spikes in those downstream neurons, thus passing down the signal.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] As many as 95% of neurons in the neocortex, the outermost layer of the mammalian brain, consist of excitatory pyramidal neurons, and each pyramidal neuron receives tens of thousands of inputs from other neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Thus, spiking neurons are a major information processing unit of the nervous system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] One such example of a spiking neuron model may be a highly detailed mathematical model that includes spatial morphology.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Another may be a conductance-based neuron model that views neurons as points and describes the membrane voltage dynamics as a function of trans-membrane currents.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] A mathematically simpler "integrate-and-fire" model significantly simplifies the description of ion channel and membrane potential dynamics (initially studied by Lapique in 1907).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Not all the cells of the nervous system produce the type of spike that defines the scope of the spiking neuron models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For example, cochlear hair cells, retinal receptor cells, and retinal bipolar cells do not spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Furthermore, many cells in the nervous system are not classified as neurons but instead are classified as glia.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Neuronal activity can be measured with different experimental techniques, such as the "Whole cell" measurement technique, which captures the spiking activity of a single neuron and produces full amplitude action potentials.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] With extracellular measurement techniques, one or more electrodes are placed in the extracellular space.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Spikes, often from several spiking sources, depending on the size of the electrode and its proximity to the sources, can be identified with signal processing techniques.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Neuron models can be divided into two categories according to the physical units of the interface of the model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Natural stimulus or pharmacological input neuron models – The models in this category connect the input stimulus, which can be either pharmacological or natural, to the probability of a spike event.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The input stage of these models is not electrical but rather has either pharmacological (chemical) concentration units, or physical units that characterize an external stimulus such as light, sound, or other forms of physical pressure.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Furthermore, the output stage represents the probability of a spike event and not an electrical voltage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Although it is not unusual in science and engineering to have several descriptive models for different abstraction/detail levels, the number of different, sometimes contradicting, biological neuron models is exceptionally high.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This situation is partly the result of the many different experimental settings, and the difficulty to separate the intrinsic properties of a single neuron from measurement effects and interactions of many cells (network effects).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Ultimately, biological neuron models aim to explain the mechanisms underlying the operation of the nervous system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] However, several approaches can be distinguished, from more realistic models (e.g., mechanistic models) to more pragmatic models (e.g., phenomenological models).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Modeling helps to analyze experimental data and address questions.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Models are also important in the context of restoring lost brain functionality through neuroprosthetic devices.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The models in this category describe the relationship between neuronal membrane currents at the input stage and membrane voltage at the output stage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This category includes (generalized) integrate-and-fire models and biophysical models inspired by the work of Hodgkin–Huxley in the early 1950s using an experimental setup that punctured the cell membrane and allowed to force a specific membrane voltage/current.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Most modern electrical neural interfaces apply extra-cellular electrical stimulation to avoid membrane puncturing, which can lead to cell death and tissue damage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Hence, it is not clear to what extent the electrical neuron models hold for extra-cellular stimulation (see e.g.).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The Hodgkin–Huxley model (H&H model) is a model of the relationship between the flow of ionic currents across the neuronal cell membrane and the membrane voltage of the cell.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] It consists of a set of nonlinear differential equations describing the behavior of ion channels that permeate the cell membrane of the squid giant axon.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Hodgkin and Huxley were awarded the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for this work.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The above equation is the time derivative of the law of capacitance, *Q* = *CV* where the change of the total charge must be explained as the sum over the currents.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where *g*(*t*,*V*) is the conductance, or inverse resistance, which can be expanded in terms of its maximal conductance *ḡ* and the activation and inactivation fractions *m* and *h*, respectively, that determine how many ions can flow through available membrane channels.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] with similar dynamics for *h*, where we can use either *τ* and *m*∞ or *α* and *β* to define our gate fractions.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The Hodgkin–Huxley model may be extended to include additional ionic currents.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Typically, these include inward Ca2+ and Na+ input currents, as well as several varieties of K+ outward currents, including a "leak" current.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The result can be at the small end of 20 parameters which one must estimate or measure for an accurate model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In a model of a complex system of neurons, numerical integration of the equations are computationally expensive.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Careful simplifications of the Hodgkin–Huxley model are therefore needed.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model can be reduced to two dimensions thanks to the dynamic relations which can be established between the gating variables. it is also possible to extend it to take into account the evolution of the concentrations (considered fixed in the original model).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] One of the earliest models of a neuron is the perfect integrate-and-fire model (also called non-leaky integrate-and-fire), first investigated in 1907 by Louis Lapicque.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] which is just the time derivative of the law of capacitance, *Q* = *CV*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] When an input current is applied, the membrane voltage increases with time until it reaches a constant threshold *V*th, at which point a delta function spike occurs and the voltage is reset to its resting potential, after which the model continues to run.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The *firing frequency* of the model thus increases linearly without bound as input current increases.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model can be made more accurate by introducing a refractory period *t*ref that limits the firing frequency of a neuron by preventing it from firing during that period.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For constant input *I(t)=I* the threshold voltage is reached after an integration time tint=CVthr/I after starting from zero.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] After a reset, the refractory period introduces a dead time so that the total time until the next firing is *t*ref+*t*int .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The firing frequency is the inverse of the total inter-spike interval (including dead time).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] A shortcoming of this model is that it describes neither adaptation nor leakage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] If the model receives a below-threshold short current pulse at some time, it will retain that voltage boost forever - until another input later makes it fire.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This characteristic is not in line with observed neuronal behavior.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The following extensions make the integrate-and-fire model more plausible from a biological point of view.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The leaky integrate-and-fire model, which can be traced back to Louis Lapicque, contains a "leak" term in the membrane potential equation that reflects the diffusion of ions through the membrane, unlike the non-leaky integrate-and-fire model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where *V*m is the voltage across the cell membrane and *R*m is the membrane resistance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] (The non-leaky integrate-and-fire model is retrieved in the limit *R*m to infinity, i.e. if the membrane is a perfect insulator).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model equation is valid for arbitrary time-dependent input until a threshold *V*th is reached; thereafter the membrane potential is reset.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For constant input, the minimum input to reach the threshold is *I*th = *V*th / *R*m.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] which converges for large input currents to the previous leak-free model with the refractory period.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model can also be used for inhibitory neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The most significant disadvantage of this model is that it does not contain neuronal adaptation, so that it cannot describe an experimentally measured spike train in response to constant input current.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This disadvantage is removed in generalized integrate-and-fire models that also contain one or several adaptation-variables and are able to predict spike times of cortical neurons under current injection to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Neuronal adaptation refers to the fact that even in the presence of a constant current injection into the soma, the intervals between output spikes increase.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where $\tau _{m}$ is the membrane time constant, *w*k is the adaptation current number, with index *k*, $\tau _{k}$ is the time constant of adaptation current *w**k*, *E*m is the resting potential and *t*f is the firing time of the neuron and the Greek delta denotes the Dirac delta function.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Whenever the voltage reaches the firing threshold the voltage is reset to a value *V*r below the firing threshold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The reset value is one of the important parameters of the model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The simplest model of adaptation has only a single adaptation variable *w* and the sum over k is removed.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Integrate-and-fire neurons with one or several adaptation variables can account for a variety of neuronal firing patterns in response to constant stimulation, including adaptation, bursting, and initial bursting.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Moreover, adaptive integrate-and-fire neurons with several adaptation variables are able to predict spike times of cortical neurons under time-dependent current injection into the soma.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Recent advances in computational and theoretical fractional calculus lead to a new form of model called Fractional-order leaky integrate-and-fire.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] An advantage of this model is that it can capture adaptation effects with a single variable.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Once the voltage hits the threshold it is reset.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Fractional integration has been used to account for neuronal adaptation in experimental data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where V is the membrane potential, $V_{T}$ is the intrinsic membrane potential threshold, $\tau _{m}$ is the membrane time constant, $E_{m}$ is the resting potential, and $\Delta _{T}$ is the sharpness of action potential initiation, usually around 1 mV for cortical pyramidal neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Once the membrane potential crosses $V_{T}$ , it diverges to infinity in finite time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In numerical simulation the integration is stopped if the membrane potential hits an arbitrary threshold (much larger than $V_{T}$ ) at which the membrane potential is reset to a value *V*r .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The voltage reset value *V*r is one of the important parameters of the model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Importantly, the right-hand side of the above equation contains a nonlinearity that can be directly extracted from experimental data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In this sense the exponential nonlinearity is strongly supported by experimental evidence.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where *w* denotes the adaptation current with time scale $\tau$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Important model parameters are the voltage reset value *V*r, the intrinsic threshold $V_{T}$ , the time constants $\tau$ and $\tau _{m}$ as well as the coupling parameters *a* and *b*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The adaptive exponential integrate-and-fire model inherits the experimentally derived voltage nonlinearity of the exponential integrate-and-fire model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] But going beyond this model, it can also account for a variety of neuronal firing patterns in response to constant stimulation, including adaptation, bursting, and initial bursting.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] However, since the adaptation is in the form of a current, aberrant hyperpolarization may appear.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This problem was solved by expressing it as a conductance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In this model, a time-dependent function $\theta (t)$ is added to the fixed threshold, $v_{th0}$ , after every spike, causing an adaptation of the threshold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The threshold potential, $v_{th}$ , gradually returns to its steady state value depending on the threshold adaptation time constant $\tau _{\theta }$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This is one of the simpler techniques to achieve spike frequency adaptation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] A simpler version of this with a single time constant in threshold decay with an LIF neuron is realized in to achieve LSTM like recurrent spiking neural networks to achieve accuracy nearer to ANNs on few spatio temporal tasks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The DEXAT neuron model is a flavor of adaptive neuron model in which the threshold voltage decays with a double exponential having two time constants.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Double exponential decay is governed by a fast initial decay and then a slower decay over a longer period of time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This neuron used in SNNs through surrogate gradient creates an adaptive learning rate yielding higher accuracy and faster convergence, and flexible long short-term memory compared to existing counterparts in the literature.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Further, multi-time scale adaptive threshold neuron model showing more complex dynamics is shown in.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The models in this category are generalized integrate-and-fire models that include a certain level of stochasticity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Cortical neurons in experiments are found to respond reliably to time-dependent input, albeit with a small degree of variations between one trial and the next if the same stimulus is repeated.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Stochasticity in neurons has two important sources.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] First, even in a very controlled experiment where input current is injected directly into the soma, ion channels open and close stochastically and this channel noise leads to a small amount of variability in the exact value of the membrane potential and the exact timing of output spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Second, for a neuron embedded in a cortical network, it is hard to control the exact input because most inputs come from unobserved neurons somewhere else in the brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The relation of noise in neuron models to the variability of spike trains and neural codes is discussed in Neural Coding and in Chapter 7 of the textbook Neuronal Dynamics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] A neuron embedded in a network receives spike input from other neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Since the spike arrival times are not controlled by an experimentalist they can be considered as stochastic.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Thus a (potentially nonlinear) integrate-and-fire model with nonlinearity f(v) receives two inputs: an input $I(t)$ controlled by the experimentalists and a noisy input current $I^{\rm {noise}}(t)$ that describes the uncontrolled background input.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] However, in contrast to the standard Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, the membrane voltage is reset whenever *V* hits the firing threshold *V*th .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Calculating the interval distribution of the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck model for constant input with threshold leads to a first-passage time problem.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Stein's neuron model and variants thereof have been used to fit interspike interval distributions of spike trains from real neurons under constant input current.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where $\sigma$ is the amplitude of the noise input and *dW* are increments of a Wiener process.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where y is drawn from a Gaussian distribution with zero mean unit variance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The voltage is reset when it hits the firing threshold *V*th .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The noisy input model can also be used in generalized integrate-and-fire models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For constant deterministic input $I(t)=I_{0}$ it is possible to calculate the mean firing rate as a function of $I_{0}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This is important because the frequency-current relation (f-I-curve) is often used by experimentalists to characterize a neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The leaky integrate-and-fire with noisy input has been widely used in the analysis of networks of spiking neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Noisy input is also called 'diffusive noise' because it leads to a diffusion of the subthreshold membrane potential around the noise-free trajectory (Johannesma, The theory of spiking neurons with noisy input is reviewed in Chapter 8.2 of the textbook *Neuronal Dynamics*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In deterministic integrate-and-fire models, a spike is generated if the membrane potential *V*(t) hits the threshold $V_{th}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In noisy output models, the strict threshold is replaced by a noisy one as follows.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] that depends on the momentary difference between the membrane voltage *V*(t) and the threshold $V_{th}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where $\tau _{0}$ is a time constant that describes how quickly a spike is fired once the membrane potential reaches the threshold and $\beta$ is a sharpness parameter.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For $\beta \to \infty$ the threshold becomes sharp and spike firing occurs deterministically at the moment when the membrane potential hits the threshold from below.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The sharpness value found in experiments is $1/\beta \approx 4mV$ which means that neuronal firing becomes non-negligible as soon as the membrane potential is a few mV below the formal firing threshold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] that depends on the momentary difference between the membrane voltage *V* at time $t_{n}$ and the threshold $V_{th}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The function F is often taken as a standard sigmoidal $F(x)=0.5[1+\tanh(\gamma x)]$ with steepness parameter $\gamma$ , similar to the update dynamics in artificial neural networks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] But the functional form of F can also be derived from the stochastic intensity f in continuous time introduced above as $F(y_{n})\approx 1-\exp[y_{n}\Delta t]$ where $y_{n}=V(t_{n})-V_{th}$ is the threshold distance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Integrate-and-fire models with output noise can be used to predict the peristimulus time histogram (PSTH) of real neurons under arbitrary time-dependent input.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For non-adaptive integrate-and-fire neurons, the interval distribution under constant stimulation can be calculated from stationary renewal theory.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The spike response model (SRM) is a generalized linear model for the subthreshold membrane voltage combined with a nonlinear output noise process for spike generation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The contributions to the voltage caused by a spike at time $t^{f}$ are described by the refractory kernel $\eta (t-t^{f})$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In particular, $\eta (t-t^{f})$ describes the reset after the spike and the time course of the spike-afterpotential following a spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] It therefore expresses the consequences of refractoriness and adaptation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The voltage V(t) can be interpreted as the result of an integration of the differential equation of a leaky integrate-and-fire model coupled to an arbitrary number of spike-triggered adaptation variables.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Here $\vartheta _{0}$ is the firing threshold of an inactive neuron and $\theta _{1}(t-t^{f})$ describes the increase of the threshold after a spike at time $t^{f}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In case of a fixed threshold, one sets $\theta _{1}(t-t^{f})=0$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For $\beta \to \infty$ the threshold process is deterministic.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The time course of the filters $\eta ,\kappa ,\theta _{1}$ that characterize the spike response model can be directly extracted from experimental data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] With optimized parameters the SRM describes the time course of the subthreshold membrane voltage for time-dependent input with a precision of 2mV and can predict the timing of most output spikes with a precision of 4ms.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The SRM is closely related to linear-nonlinear-Poisson cascade models (also called Generalized Linear Model).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The estimation of parameters of probabilistic neuron models such as the SRM using methods developed for Generalized Linear Models is discussed in Chapter 10 of the textbook *Neuronal Dynamics*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The time course $\varepsilon _{ij}(s)$ of the PSP results from the convolution of the postsynaptic current $I(t)$ caused by the arrival of a presynaptic spike from neuron j with the membrane filter $\kappa (s)$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The **SRM0** is a stochastic neuron model related to time-dependent nonlinear renewal theory and a simplification of the Spike Response Model (SRM).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The main difference to the voltage equation of the SRM introduced above is that in the term containing the refractory kernel $\eta (s)$ there is no summation sign over past spikes: only the *most recent spike* (denoted as the time ${\hat {t}}$ ) matters.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Another difference is that the threshold is constant.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model SRM0 can be formulated in discrete or continuous time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where ${\hat {t}}_{i}$ is the *last firing time neuron* i.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Note that the time course of the postsynaptic potential $\varepsilon _{ij}$ is also allowed to depend on the time since the last spike of neuron i to describe a change in membrane conductance during refractoriness.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where $V_{th}$ is a fixed firing threshold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Thus spike firing of neuron i depends only on its input and the time since neuron i has fired its last spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] With the SRM0, the interspike-interval distribution for constant input can be mathematically linked to the shape of the refractory kernel $\eta$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Moreover the stationary frequency-current relation can be calculated from the escape rate in combination with the refractory kernel $\eta$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] With an appropriate choice of the kernels, the SRM0 approximates the dynamics of the Hodgkin-Huxley model to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Moreover, the PSTH response to arbitrary time-dependent input can be predicted.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The models in this category are highly simplified toy models that qualitatively describe the membrane voltage as a function of input.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] They are mainly used for didactic reasons in teaching but are not considered valid neuron models for large-scale simulations or data fitting.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Sweeping simplifications to Hodgkin–Huxley were introduced by FitzHugh and Nagumo in 1961 and 1962.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where we again have a membrane-like voltage and input current with a slower general gate voltage *w* and experimentally-determined parameters *a* = -0.7, *b* = 0.8, *τ* = 1/0.08.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Although not derivable from biology, the model allows for a simplified, immediately available dynamic, without being a trivial simplification.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The experimental support is weak, but the model is useful as a didactic tool to introduce dynamics of spike generation through phase plane analysis.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] See Chapter 7 in the textbook *Methods of Neuronal Modeling*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The experimental support of the model is weak, but the model is useful as a didactic tool to introduce dynamics of spike generation through phase plane analysis.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] A two-dimensional neuron model very similar to the Morris-Lecar model can be derived step-by-step starting from the Hodgkin-Huxley model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] See Chapter 4.2 in the textbook Neuronal Dynamics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] with *r*2 = *x*2 + *y*2 + *z*2, and *r* ≈ 10−2 so that the *z* variable only changes very slowly.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This extra mathematical complexity allows a great variety of dynamic behaviors for the membrane potential, described by the *x* variable of the model, which includes chaotic dynamics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] This makes the Hindmarsh–Rose neuron model very useful, because it is still simple, allows a good qualitative description of the many different firing patterns of the action potential, in particular bursting, observed in experiments.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Nevertheless, it remains a toy model and has not been fitted to experimental data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] It is widely used as a reference model for bursting dynamics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The theta model, or Ermentrout–Kopell canonical Type I model, is mathematically equivalent to the quadratic integrate-and-fire model which in turn is an approximation to the exponential integrate-and-fire model and the Hodgkin-Huxley model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] It is called a canonical model because it is one of the generic models for constant input close to the bifurcation point, which means close to the transition from silent to repetitive firing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The equivalence of theta model and quadratic integrate-and-fire is for example reviewed in Chapter 4.1.2.2 of spiking neuron models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The models in this category were derived following experiments involving natural stimulation such as light, sound, touch, or odor.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In these experiments, the spike pattern resulting from each stimulus presentation varies from trial to trial, but the averaged response from several trials often converges to a clear pattern.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Consequently, the models in this category generate a probabilistic relationship between the input stimulus to spike occurrences.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Siebert modeled the neuron spike firing pattern using a non-homogeneous Poisson process model, following experiments involving the auditory system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Siebert considered several functions as $g[s(t)]$ , including $g[s(t)]\propto s^{2}(t)$ for low stimulus intensities.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The main advantage of Siebert's model is its simplicity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] These shortcomings are addressed by the age-dependent point process model and the two-state Markov Model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model is also called an *inhomogeneous Markov interval (IMI) process*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Similar models have been used for many years in auditory neuroscience.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Since the model keeps memory of the last spike time it is non-Poisson and falls in the class of time-dependent renewal models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] It is closely related to the model SRM0 with exponential escape rate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Importantly, it is possible to fit parameters of the age-dependent point process model so as to describe not just the PSTH response, but also the interspike-interval statistics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The linear-nonlinear-Poisson cascade model is a cascade of a linear filtering process followed by a nonlinear spike generation step.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] In the case that output spikes feed back, via a linear filtering process, we arrive at a model that is known in the neurosciences as Generalized Linear Model (GLM).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The spiking neuron model by Nossenson & Messer produces the probability of the neuron firing a spike as a function of either an external or pharmacological stimulus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The model consists of a cascade of a receptor layer model and a spiking neuron model, as shown in Fig 4.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Thus, the spiking neuron model by itself depends on neurotransmitter concentration at the input stage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] An important feature of this model is the prediction for neurons firing rate pattern which captures, using a low number of free parameters, the characteristic edge emphasized response of neurons to a stimulus pulse, as shown in Fig.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The firing rate is identified both as a normalized probability for neural spike firing and as a quantity proportional to the current of neurotransmitters released by the cell.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] P0 could be generally calculated recursively using the Euler method, but in the case of a pulse of stimulus, it yields a simple closed-form expression.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] with $\langle s^{2}(t)\rangle$ being a short temporal average of stimulus power (given in Watt or other energy per time unit).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] 1) The averaged evoked response potential (ERP) due to the population of many neurons in unfiltered measurements resembles the firing rate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] 2) The voltage variance of activity due to multiple neuron activity resembles the firing rate (also known as Multi-Unit-Activity power or MUA).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] 3) The inter-spike-interval probability distribution takes the form a gamma-distribution like function.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The models in this category produce predictions for experiments involving pharmacological stimulation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] According to the model by Koch and Segev, the response of a neuron to individual neurotransmitters can be modeled as an extension of the classical Hodgkin–Huxley model with both standard and nonstandard kinetic currents.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Four neurotransmitters primarily influence the CNS.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] AMPA/kainate receptors are fast excitatory mediators while NMDA receptors mediate considerably slower currents.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] Fast inhibitory currents go through GABAA receptors, while GABAB receptors mediate by secondary *G*-protein-activated potassium channels.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] where *ḡ* is the maximal conductance (around 1S) and *E* is the equilibrium potential of the given ion or transmitter (AMDA, NMDA, Cl, or K), while [*O*] describes the fraction of open receptors.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For NMDA, there is a significant effect of *magnesium block* that depends sigmoidally on the concentration of intracellular magnesium by *B*(*V*).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For GABAB, [*G*] is the concentration of the *G*-protein, and *K*d describes the dissociation of *G* in binding to the potassium gates.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The dynamics of this more complicated model have been well-studied experimentally and produce important results in terms of very quick synaptic potentiation and depression, that is fast, short-term learning.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The stochastic **model by Nossenson and Messer** translates neurotransmitter concentration at the input stage to the probability of releasing neurotransmitter at the output stage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] For a more detailed description of this model, see the Two state Markov model section above.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] The HTM neuron model was developed by Jeff Hawkins and researchers at Numenta and is based on a theory called Hierarchical Temporal Memory, originally described in the book *On Intelligence*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p01] It is based on neuroscience and the physiology and interaction of pyramidal neurons in the neocortex of the human brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Spiking Neuron Models are used in a variety of applications that need encoding into or decoding from neuronal spike trains in the context of neuroprosthesis and brain-computer interfaces such as retinal prosthesis: or artificial limb control and sensation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Applications are not part of this article; for more information on this topic please refer to the main article.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The most basic model of a neuron consists of an input with some synaptic weight vector and an activation function or transfer function inside the neuron determining output.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] where *y**i* is the output of the *i* th neuron, *x**j* is the *j*th input neuron signal, *w**ij* is the synaptic weight (or strength of connection) between the neurons *i* and *j*, and *φ* is the activation function.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] While this model has seen success in machine-learning applications, it is a poor model for real (biological) neurons, because it lacks time-dependence in input and output.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] When an input is switched on at a time t and kept constant thereafter, biological neurons emit a spike train.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Importantly, this spike train is not regular but exhibits a temporal structure characterized by adaptation, bursting, or initial bursting followed by regular spiking.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Generalized integrate-and-fire models such as the Adaptive Exponential Integrate-and-Fire model, the spike response model, or the (linear) adaptive integrate-and-fire model can capture these neuronal firing patterns.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Moreover, neuronal input in the brain is time-dependent.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Time-dependent input is transformed by complex linear and nonlinear filters into a spike train in the output.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Again, the spike response model or the adaptive integrate-and-fire model enables to prediction of the spike train in the output for arbitrary time-dependent input, whereas an artificial neuron or a simple leaky integrate-and-fire does not.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] If we take the Hodkgin-Huxley model as a starting point, generalized integrate-and-fire models can be derived systematically in a step-by-step simplification procedure.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] This has been shown explicitly for the exponential integrate-and-fire model and the spike response model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] In the case of modeling a biological neuron, physical analogs are used in place of abstractions such as "weight" and "transfer function".
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] A neuron is filled and surrounded with water-containing ions, which carry electric charge.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The neuron is bound by an insulating cell membrane and can maintain a concentration of charged ions on either side that determines a capacitance *C*m.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The firing of a neuron involves the movement of ions into the cell, that occurs when neurotransmitters cause ion channels on the cell membrane to open.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] We describe this by a physical time-dependent current *I*(*t*).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] With this comes a change in voltage, or the electrical potential energy difference between the cell and its surroundings, which is observed to sometimes result in a voltage spike called an action potential which travels the length of the cell and triggers the release of further neurotransmitters.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The voltage, then, is the quantity of interest and is given by *V*m(*t*).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] If the input current is constant, most neurons emit after some time of adaptation or initial bursting a regular spike train.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The frequency of regular firing in response to a constant current *I* is described by the frequency-current relation, which corresponds to the transfer function $\varphi$ of artificial neural networks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Similarly, for all spiking neuron models, the transfer function $\varphi$ can be calculated numerically (or analytically).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] All of the above deterministic models are point-neuron models because they do not consider the spatial structure of a neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] However, the dendrite contributes to transforming input into output.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Point neuron models are valid description in three cases.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] (i) If input current is directly injected into the soma.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] (ii) If synaptic input arrives predominantly at or close to the soma (closeness is defined by a length scale $\lambda$ introduced below.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] (iii) If synapse arrives anywhere on the dendrite, but the dendrite is completely linear.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] In the last case, the cable acts as a linear filter; these linear filter properties can be included in the formulation of generalized integrate-and-fire models such as the spike response model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The filter properties can be calculated from a cable equation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Let us consider a cell membrane in the form of a cylindrical cable.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The position on the cable is denoted by x and the voltage across the cell membrane by V.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The cable is characterized by a longitudinal resistance $r_{l}$ per unit length and a membrane resistance $r_{m}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] We introduce a length scale $\lambda ^{2}={r_{m}}/{r_{l}}$ on the left side and time constant $\tau =c_{m}r_{m}$ on the right side.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The above cable equation is valid for a single cylindrical cable.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Linear cable theory describes the dendritic arbor of a neuron as a cylindrical structure undergoing a regular pattern of bifurcation, like branches in a tree.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] where *L* is the electrotonic length of the cylinder, which depends on its length, diameter, and resistance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] A simple recursive algorithm scales linearly with the number of branches and can be used to calculate the effective conductance of the tree.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] where *A**D* = *πld* is the total surface area of the tree of total length *l*, and *L**D* is its total electrotonic length.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] where we can find the general correction factor *F**dga* experimentally by noting *G**D* = *G**md**A**D**F**dga*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The linear cable model makes several simplifications to give closed analytic results, namely that the dendritic arbor must branch in diminishing pairs in a fixed pattern and that dendrites are linear.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] A compartmental model allows for any desired tree topology with arbitrary branches and lengths, as well as arbitrary nonlinearities.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] It is essentially a discretized computational implementation of nonlinear dendrites.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Each piece, or compartment, of a dendrite, is modeled by a straight cylinder of arbitrary length *l* and diameter *d* which connects with fixed resistance to any number of branching cylinders.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] We define the conductance ratio of the *i*th cylinder as *B**i* = *G**i* / *G*∞, where $G_{\infty }={\tfrac {\pi d^{3/2}}{2{\sqrt {R_{i}R_{m}}}}}$ and *R**i* is the resistance between the current compartment and the next.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] We can iterate these equations through the tree until we get the point where the dendrites connect to the cell body (soma), where the conductance ratio is *B*in,stem.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Importantly, static input is a very special case.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Moreover, dendrites are not always linear.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Compartmental models enable to include nonlinearities via ion channels positioned at arbitrary locations along the dendrites.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] For static inputs, it is sometimes possible to reduce the number of compartments (increase the computational speed) and yet retain the salient electrical characteristics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The neurotransmitter-based energy detection scheme suggests that the neural tissue chemically executes a Radar-like detection procedure.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The detection scheme is similar to a radar-like "energy detection" because it includes signal squaring, temporal summation, and a threshold switch mechanism, just like the energy detector, but it also includes a unit that emphasizes stimulus edges and a variable memory length (variable memory).
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] According to this conjecture, the physiological equivalent of the energy test statistics is neurotransmitter concentration, and the firing rate corresponds to neurotransmitter current.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] The advantage of this interpretation is that it leads to a unit-consistent explanation which allows for bridge between electrophysiological measurements, biochemical measurements, and psychophysical results.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Stimulus edge emphasizing and signal transduction is performed by neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Temporal accumulation of neurotransmitters is performed by glial cells.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Short-term neurotransmitter accumulation is likely to occur also in some types of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Logical switching is executed by glial cells, and it results from exceeding a threshold level of neurotransmitter concentration.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] This threshold crossing is also accompanied by a change in neurotransmitter leak rate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Physical all-or-non movement switching is due to muscle cells and results from exceeding a certain neurotransmitter concentration threshold on muscle surroundings.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] Note that although the electrophysiological signals in Fig.6 are often similar to the functional signal (signal power/neurotransmitter concentration / muscle force), there are some stages in which the electrical observation differs from the functional purpose of the corresponding step.
[src:computational-neuroscience/biological-neuron-model-p02] In particular, Nossenson et al. suggested that glia threshold crossing has a completely different functional operation compared to the radiated electrophysiological signal and that the latter might only be a side effect of glia break.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] In neuroscience, classical **cable theory** uses mathematical models to calculate the electric current (and accompanying voltage) along passive neurites, particularly the dendrites that receive synaptic inputs at different sites and times.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Estimates are made by modeling dendrites and axons as cylinders composed of segments with capacitances $c_{m}$ and resistances $r_{m}$ combined in parallel (see Fig.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The capacitance of a neuronal fiber comes about because electrostatic forces are acting through the very thin lipid bilayer (see Figure 2).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The resistance in series along the fiber $r_{l}$ is due to the axoplasm's significant resistance to movement of electric charge.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Cable theory in computational neuroscience has roots leading back to the 1850s, when Professor William Thomson (later known as Lord Kelvin) began developing mathematical models of signal decay in submarine (underwater) telegraphic cables.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The models resembled the partial differential equations used by Fourier to describe heat conduction in a wire.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The 1870s saw the first attempts by Hermann to model neuronal electrotonic potentials also by focusing on analogies with heat conduction.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] However, it was Hoorweg who first discovered the analogies with Kelvin's undersea cables in 1898 and then Hermann and Cremer who independently developed the cable theory for neuronal fibers in the early 20th century.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Further mathematical theories of nerve fiber conduction based on cable theory were developed by Cole and Hodgkin (1920s–1930s), Offner et al.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Experimental evidence for the importance of cable theory in modelling the behavior of axons began surfacing in the 1930s from work done by Cole, Curtis, Hodgkin, Sir Bernard Katz, Rushton, Tasaki and others.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Two key papers from this era are those of Davis and Lorente de Nó (1947) and Hodgkin and Rushton (1946).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The 1950s saw improvements in techniques for measuring the electric activity of individual neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Thus cable theory became important for analyzing data collected from intracellular microelectrode recordings and for analyzing the electrical properties of neuronal dendrites.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Scientists like Coombs, Eccles, Fatt, Frank, Fuortes and others now relied heavily on cable theory to obtain functional insights of neurons and for guiding them in the design of new experiments.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Later, cable theory with its mathematical derivatives allowed ever more sophisticated neuron models to be explored by workers such as Jack, Rall, Redman, Rinzel, Idan Segev, Tuckwell, Bell, and Iannella.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] More recently, cable theory has been applied to model electrical activity in bundled neurons in the white matter of the brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Note, various conventions of *r**m* exist.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Here *r**m* and *c**m*, as introduced above, are measured per membrane-length unit (per meter (m)).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Thus *r**m* is measured in ohm·meters (Ω·m) and *c**m* in farads per meter (F/m).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] This is in contrast to *R**m* (in Ω·m2) and *C**m* (in F/m2), which represent the specific resistance and capacitance respectively of one unit area of membrane (in m2).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The greater the cross sectional area of the axon, *πa*2, the greater the number of paths for the charge to flow through its axoplasm, and the lower the axoplasmic resistance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Several important avenues of extending classical cable theory have recently seen the introduction of endogenous structures in order to analyze the effects of protein polarization within dendrites and different synaptic input distributions over the dendritic surface of a neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] To better understand how the cable equation is derived, first consider an idealized neuron with a perfectly sealed membrane (*r**m*=∞) with no loss of current to the outside, and no capacitance (*c**m* = 0).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] A current injected into the fiber at position *x* = 0 would move along the inside of the fiber unchanged.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] where the negative is because current flows down the potential gradient.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Bringing *r**m* back into the picture is like making holes in a garden hose.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The more holes, the faster the water will escape from the hose, and the less water will travel all the way from the beginning of the hose to the end.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Similarly, in an axon, some of the current traveling longitudinally through the axoplasm will escape through the membrane.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] If *i**m* is the current escaping through the membrane per length unit, m, then the total current escaping along *y* units must be *y·i**m*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] $i_{m}$ can be expressed with yet another formula, by including the capacitance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The capacitance will cause a flow of charge (a current) towards the membrane on the side of the cytoplasm.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] where $c_{m}$ is the membrane's capacitance and ${\partial V}/{\partial t}$ is the change in voltage over time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] where ${\partial i_{l}}/{\partial x}$ represents the change per unit length of the longitudinal current.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] which is a second-order partial differential equation (PDE).
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] By a simple rearrangement of equation (**12**) (see later) it is possible to make two important terms appear, namely the length constant (sometimes referred to as the space constant) denoted $\lambda$ and the time constant denoted $\tau$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The following sections focus on these terms.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The length constant, $\lambda$ (lambda), is a parameter that indicates how far a stationary current will influence the voltage along the cable.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The larger the value of $\lambda$ , the farther the charge will flow.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The larger the membrane resistance, *r**m*, the greater the value of $\lambda$ , and the more current will remain inside the axoplasm to travel longitudinally through the axon.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The higher the axoplasmic resistance, $r_{l}$ , the smaller the value of $\lambda$ , the harder it will be for current to travel through the axoplasm, and the shorter the current will be able to travel.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Where $V_{0}$ is the depolarization at $x=0$ (point of current injection), *e* is the exponential constant (approximate value 2.71828) and $V_{x}$ is the voltage at a given distance *x* from *x*=0.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Neuroscientists are often interested in knowing how fast the membrane potential, $V_{m}$ , of an axon changes in response to changes in the current injected into the axoplasm.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The larger the membrane capacitance, $c_{m}$ , the more current it takes to charge and discharge a patch of membrane and the longer this process will take.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] The larger the membrane resistance $r_{m}$ , the harder it is for a current to induce a change in membrane potential.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] So the higher the $\tau$ the slower the nerve impulse can travel.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] That means, membrane potential (voltage across the membrane) lags more behind current injections.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] Response times vary from 1–2 milliseconds in neurons that are processing information that needs high temporal precision to 100 milliseconds or longer.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] A typical response time is around 20 milliseconds.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] This is a 1D heat equation or diffusion equation for which many solution methods, such as Green's functions and Fourier methods, have been developed.
[src:computational-neuroscience/cable-theory] It is also a special degenerate case of the Telegrapher's equation, where the inductance L vanishes and the signal propagation speed $1/{\sqrt {LC}}$ is infinite.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational neuroscience employs computational simulations to validate and solve mathematical models, and so can be seen as a sub-field of theoretical neuroscience; however, the two fields are often synonymous.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The term mathematical neuroscience is also used sometimes, to stress the quantitative nature of the field.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational neuroscience focuses on the description of biologically plausible neurons (and neural systems) and their physiology and dynamics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] These computational models frame hypotheses that can be directly tested by biological or psychological experiments.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The term 'computational neuroscience' was introduced by Eric L.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The proceedings of this definitional meeting were published in 1990 as the book *Computational Neuroscience*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The first of the annual open international meetings focused on Computational Neuroscience was organized by James M.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Bower and John Miller in San Francisco, California in 1989.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The first graduate educational program in computational neuroscience was organized as the Computation and Neural Systems Ph.D. program at the California Institute of Technology in 1986.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The early historical roots of the field can be traced to the work of people including Louis Lapicque, Hodgkin & Huxley, Hubel and Wiesel, and David Marr.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Lapicque introduced the integrate and fire model of the neuron in a seminal article published in 1907, a model still popular for artificial neural networks studies because of its simplicity (see a recent review).
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] About 40 years later, Hodgkin and Huxley developed the voltage clamp and created the first biophysical model of the action potential.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Hubel and Wiesel discovered that neurons in the primary visual cortex, the first cortical area to process information coming from the retina, have oriented receptive fields and are organized in columns.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] David Marr's work focused on the interactions between neurons, suggesting computational approaches to the study of how functional groups of neurons within the hippocampus and neocortex interact, store, process, and transmit information.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational modeling of biophysically realistic neurons and dendrites began with the work of Wilfrid Rall, with the first multicompartmental model using cable theory.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Research in computational neuroscience can be roughly categorized into several lines of inquiry.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Most computational neuroscientists collaborate closely with experimentalists in analyzing novel data and synthesizing new models of biological phenomena.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Even a single neuron has complex biophysical characteristics and can perform computations (e.g.).
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Though successful in predicting the timing and qualitative features of the action potential, it nevertheless failed to predict a number of important features such as adaptation and shunting.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Scientists now believe that there are a wide variety of voltage-sensitive currents, and the implications of the differing dynamics, modulations, and sensitivity of these currents is an important topic of computational neuroscience.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The computational functions of complex dendrites are also under intense investigation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] There is a large body of literature regarding how different currents interact with geometric properties of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] There are many software packages, such as GENESIS and NEURON, that allow rapid and systematic *in silico* modeling of realistic neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Blue Brain, a project founded by Henry Markram from the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne, aims to construct a biophysically detailed simulation of a cortical column on the Blue Gene supercomputer.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Modeling the richness of biophysical properties on the single-neuron scale can supply mechanisms that serve as the building blocks for network dynamics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] However, detailed neuron descriptions are computationally expensive and this computing cost can limit the pursuit of realistic network investigations, where many neurons need to be simulated.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] As a result, researchers that study large neural circuits typically represent each neuron and synapse with an artificially simple model, ignoring much of the biological detail.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Hence there is a drive to produce simplified neuron models that can retain significant biological fidelity at a low computational overhead.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Algorithms have been developed to produce faithful, faster running, simplified surrogate neuron models from computationally expensive, detailed neuron models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Glial cells participate significantly in the regulation of neuronal activity at both the cellular and the network level.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Modeling this interaction allows to clarify the potassium cycle, so important for maintaining homeostasis and to prevent epileptic seizures.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Modeling reveals the role of glial protrusions that can penetrate in some cases the synaptic cleft to interfere with the synaptic transmission and thus control synaptic communication.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational neuroscience aims to address a wide array of questions, including: How do axons and dendrites form during development?
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] How do axons know where to target and how to reach these targets?
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] How do neurons migrate to the proper position in the central and peripheral systems?
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] We know from molecular biology that distinct parts of the nervous system release distinct chemical cues, from growth factors to hormones that modulate and influence the growth and development of functional connections between neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Theoretical investigations into the formation and patterning of synaptic connection and morphology are still nascent.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] One hypothesis that has recently garnered some attention is the *minimal wiring hypothesis*, which postulates that the formation of axons and dendrites effectively minimizes resource allocation while maintaining maximal information storage.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Early models on sensory processing understood within a theoretical framework are credited to Horace Barlow.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Somewhat similar to the minimal wiring hypothesis described in the preceding section, Barlow understood the processing of the early sensory systems to be a form of efficient coding, where the neurons encoded information which minimized the number of spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Experimental and computational work have since supported this hypothesis in one form or another.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] For the example of visual processing, efficient coding is manifested in the forms of efficient spatial coding, color coding, temporal/motion coding, stereo coding, and combinations of them.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Further along the visual pathway, even the efficiently coded visual information is too much for the capacity of the information bottleneck, the visual attentional bottleneck.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] A subsequent theory, V1 Saliency Hypothesis (V1SH), has been developed on exogenous attentional selection of a fraction of visual input for further processing, guided by a bottom-up saliency map in the primary visual cortex.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Current research in sensory processing is divided among a biophysical modeling of different subsystems and a more theoretical modeling of perception.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Current models of perception have suggested that the brain performs some form of Bayesian inference and integration of different sensory information in generating our perception of the physical world.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Many models of the way the brain controls movement have been developed.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] This includes models of processing in the brain such as the cerebellum's role for error correction, skill learning in motor cortex and the basal ganglia, or the control of the vestibulo ocular reflex.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] This also includes many normative models, such as those of the Bayesian or optimal control flavor which are built on the idea that the brain efficiently solves its problems.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Earlier models of memory are primarily based on the postulates of Hebbian learning.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Biologically relevant models such as Hopfield net have been developed to address the properties of associative (also known as "content-addressable") style of memory that occur in biological systems.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] These attempts are primarily focusing on the formation of medium- and long-term memory, localizing in the hippocampus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] One of the major problems in neurophysiological memory is how it is maintained and changed through multiple time scales.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Unstable synapses are easy to train but also prone to stochastic disruption.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Stable synapses forget less easily, but they are also harder to consolidate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] It is likely that computational tools will contribute greatly to our understanding of how synapses function and change in relation to external stimulus in the coming decades.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Biological neurons are connected to each other in a complex, recurrent fashion.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] These connections are, unlike most artificial neural networks, sparse and usually specific.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] It is not known how information is transmitted through such sparsely connected networks, although specific areas of the brain, such as the visual cortex, are understood in some detail.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] It is also unknown what the computational functions of these specific connectivity patterns are, if any.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The interactions of neurons in a small network can be often reduced to simple models such as the Ising model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The statistical mechanics of such simple systems are well-characterized theoretically.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Some recent evidence suggests that dynamics of arbitrary neuronal networks can be reduced to pairwise interactions.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] It is not known, however, whether such descriptive dynamics impart any important computational function.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] With the emergence of two-photon microscopy and calcium imaging, we now have powerful experimental methods with which to test the new theories regarding neuronal networks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] In some cases the complex interactions between *inhibitory* and *excitatory* neurons can be simplified using mean-field theory, which gives rise to the population model of neural networks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] While many neurotheorists prefer such models with reduced complexity, others argue that uncovering structural-functional relations depends on including as much neuronal and network structure as possible.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Models of this type are typically built in large simulation platforms like GENESIS or NEURON.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] There have been some attempts to provide unified methods that bridge and integrate these levels of complexity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Visual attention can be described as a set of mechanisms that limit some processing to a subset of incoming stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Attentional mechanisms shape what we see and what we can act upon.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] They allow for concurrent selection of some (preferably, relevant) information and inhibition of other information.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] In order to have a more concrete specification of the mechanism underlying visual attention and the binding of features, a number of computational models have been proposed aiming to explain psychophysical findings.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] In general, all models postulate the existence of a saliency or priority map for registering the potentially interesting areas of the retinal input, and a gating mechanism for reducing the amount of incoming visual information, so that the limited computational resources of the brain can handle it.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] An example theory that is being extensively tested behaviorally and physiologically is the V1 Saliency Hypothesis that a bottom-up saliency map is created in the primary visual cortex to guide attention exogenously.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational neuroscience provides a mathematical framework for studying the mechanisms involved in brain function and allows complete simulation and prediction of neuropsychological syndromes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational modeling of higher cognitive functions has only recently begun.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Experimental data comes primarily from single-unit recording in primates.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The frontal lobe and parietal lobe function as integrators of information from multiple sensory modalities.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] There are some tentative ideas regarding how simple mutually inhibitory functional circuits in these areas may carry out biologically relevant computation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The brain seems to be able to discriminate and adapt particularly well in certain contexts.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] For instance, human beings seem to have an enormous capacity for memorizing and recognizing faces.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] One of the key goals of computational neuroscience is to dissect how biological systems carry out these complex computations efficiently and potentially replicate these processes in building intelligent machines.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The brain's large-scale organizational principles are illuminated by many fields, including biology, psychology, and clinical practice.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Integrative neuroscience attempts to consolidate these observations through unified descriptive models and databases of behavioral measures and recordings.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] These are the bases for some quantitative modeling of large-scale brain activity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] The Computational Representational Understanding of Mind (CRUM) is another attempt at modeling human cognition through simulated processes like acquired rule-based systems in decision making and the manipulation of visual representations in decision making.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] One of the ultimate goals of psychology/neuroscience is to be able to explain the everyday experience of conscious life.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Francis Crick, Giulio Tononi and Christof Koch made some attempts to formulate consistent frameworks for future work in neural correlates of consciousness (NCC), though much of the work in this field remains speculative.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Predictive computational neuroscience is a recent field that combines signal processing, neuroscience, clinical data and machine learning to predict the brain during coma or anesthesia.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] For example, it is possible to anticipate deep brain states using the EEG signal.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] These states can be used to anticipate hypnotic concentration to administrate to the patient.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Computational psychiatry was originally conceived in the late-2000s as the application of computational models to psychiatric disorders.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] It quickly developed throughout the 2010s with research into schizophrenia, addiction, and major depression among other disorders.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] There were also attempts to develop computationally inspired diagnostic criteria via the subfield of computational nosology.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] More recent work seeks to apply Bayesian models of cognition to explain the symptomatology and phenomenology of psychiatric disorders.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] A neuromorphic computer/chip is any device that uses physical artificial neurons (made from silicon) to do computations (See: neuromorphic computing, physical neural network).
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] One of the advantages of using a physical model computer such as this is that it takes the computational load of the processor (in the sense that the structural and some of the functional elements don't have to be programmed since they are in hardware).
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] In recent times, neuromorphic technology has been used to build supercomputers which are used in international neuroscience collaborations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/computational-neuroscience] Examples include the Human Brain Project SpiNNaker supercomputer and the BrainScaleS computer.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The **Hodgkin–Huxley model**, or **conductance-based model**, is a mathematical model that describes how action potentials in neurons are initiated and propagated.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] It is a set of nonlinear differential equations that approximates the electrical engineering characteristics of excitable cells such as neurons and muscle cells.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] It is a continuous-time dynamical system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley described the model in 1952 to explain the ionic mechanisms underlying the initiation and propagation of action potentials in the squid giant axon.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] They received the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for this work.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The typical Hodgkin–Huxley model treats each component of an excitable cell as an electrical element (as shown in the figure).
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The lipid bilayer is represented as a capacitance (Cm).
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Voltage-gated ion channels are represented by electrical conductances (*g**n*, where *n* is the specific ion channel) that depend on both voltage and time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Leak channels are represented by linear conductances (*g**L*).
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The electrochemical gradients driving the flow of ions are represented by voltage sources (*E**n*) whose voltages are determined by the ratio of the intra- and extracellular concentrations of the ionic species of interest.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Finally, ion pumps are represented by current sources (*I**p*).
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The membrane potential is denoted by *Vm*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] where $V_{i}$ is the reversal potential of the specific ion channel.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The time dependent elements of this equation are *V**m*, *g**Na*, and *g**K*, where the last two conductances depend explicitly on the membrane voltage (*V**m*) as well.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] In voltage-gated ion channels, the channel conductance is a function of both time and voltage ( $g_{n}(t,V)$ in the figure), while in leak channels, $g_{l}$ , it is a constant ( $g_{L}$ in the figure).
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The current generated by ion pumps is dependent on the ionic species specific to that pump.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The following sections will describe these formulations in more detail.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Using a series of voltage clamp experiments and by varying extracellular sodium and potassium concentrations, Hodgkin and Huxley developed a model in which the properties of an excitable cell are described by a set of four ordinary differential equations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] where *I* is the current per unit area and $\alpha _{i}$ and $\beta _{i}$ are rate constants for the *i*-th ion channel, which depend on voltage but not time. ${\bar {g}}_{n}$ is the maximal value of the conductance.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] *n*, *m*, and *h* are dimensionless probabilities between 0 and 1 that are associated with potassium channel subunit activation, sodium channel subunit activation, and sodium channel subunit inactivation, respectively.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] For instance, given that potassium channels in squid giant axon are made up of four subunits which all need to be in the open state for the channel to allow the passage of potassium ions, the *n* needs to be raised to the fourth power.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] $p_{\infty }$ and $(1-p_{\infty })$ are the steady state values for activation and inactivation, respectively, and are usually represented by Boltzmann equations as functions of $V_{m}$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] where $V=V_{rest}-V_{m}$ denotes the negative depolarization in mV.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] In order to characterize voltage-gated channels, the equations can be fitted to voltage clamp data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] For a derivation of the Hodgkin–Huxley equations under voltage-clamp, see.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] In order to arrive at the complete solution for a propagated action potential, one must write the current term *I* on the left-hand side of the first differential equation in terms of *V*, so that the equation becomes an equation for voltage alone.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] where *a* is the radius of the axon, *R* is the specific resistance of the axoplasm, and *x* is the position along the nerve fiber.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Substitution of this expression for *I* transforms the original set of equations into a set of partial differential equations, because the voltage becomes a function of both *x* and *t*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm is often used to fit these equations to voltage-clamp data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] While the original experiments involved only sodium and potassium channels, the Hodgkin–Huxley model can also be extended to account for other species of ion channels.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Leak channels account for the natural permeability of the membrane to ions and take the form of the equation for voltage-gated channels, where the conductance $g_{leak}$ is a constant.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Thus, the leak current due to passive leak ion channels in the Hodgkin-Huxley formalism is $I_{l}=g_{leak}(V-V_{leak})$ .
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The membrane potential depends upon the maintenance of ionic concentration gradients across it.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The maintenance of these concentration gradients requires active transport of ionic species.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The sodium-potassium and sodium-calcium exchangers are the best known of these.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Some of the basic properties of the Na/Ca exchanger have already been well-established: the stoichiometry of exchange is 3 Na+: 1 Ca2+ and the exchanger is electrogenic and voltage-sensitive.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Na/K exchanger has also been described in detail, with a 3 Na+: 2 K+ stoichiometry.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Hodgkin–Huxley model can be thought of as a differential equation system with four state variables, $V_{m}(t),n(t),m(t)$ , and $h(t)$ , that change with respect to time t .
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The system is difficult to study because it is a nonlinear system, cannot be solved analytically, and therefore has no closed-form solution.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] However, there are many numerical methods available to analyze the system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Certain properties and general behaviors, such as limit cycles, can be proven to exist.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Because there are four state variables, visualizing the path in phase space can be difficult.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Usually two variables are chosen, voltage $V_{m}(t)$ and the potassium gating variable $n(t)$ , allowing one to visualize the limit cycle.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] However, one must be careful because this is an ad-hoc method of visualizing the 4-dimensional system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] This does not prove the existence of the limit cycle.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] A better projection can be constructed from a careful analysis of the Jacobian of the system, evaluated at the equilibrium point.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Specifically, the eigenvalues of the Jacobian are indicative of the center manifold's existence.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Likewise, the eigenvectors of the Jacobian reveal the center manifold's orientation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Hodgkin–Huxley model has two negative eigenvalues and two complex eigenvalues with slightly positive real parts.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The eigenvectors associated with the two negative eigenvalues will reduce to zero as time *t* increases.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The remaining two complex eigenvectors define the center manifold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] In other words, the 4-dimensional system collapses onto a 2-dimensional plane.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Any solution starting off the center manifold will decay towards the center manifold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Furthermore, the limit cycle is contained on the center manifold.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] If the injected current I were used as a bifurcation parameter, then the Hodgkin–Huxley model undergoes a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] As with most neuronal models, increasing the injected current will increase the firing rate of the neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] One consequence of the Hopf bifurcation is that there is a minimum firing rate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] This means that either the neuron is not firing at all (corresponding to zero frequency), or firing at the minimum firing rate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Because of the all-or-none principle, there is no smooth increase in action potential amplitude, but rather there is a sudden "jump" in amplitude.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The resulting transition is known as a canard.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Hodgkin–Huxley model is regarded as one of the great achievements of 20th-century biophysics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Several simplified neuronal models have also been developed (such as the FitzHugh–Nagumo model), facilitating efficient large-scale simulation of groups of neurons, as well as mathematical insight into dynamics of action potential generation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/hodgkin-huxley-model] Ion-channel parameters derived from Hodgkin–Huxley-type models fitted to single-cell electrophysiological data have been shown to correlate with single-cell transcriptomic profiles across neuronal cell types, underscoring the biological realism of such models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Neurons have an ability uncommon among the cells of the body to propagate signals rapidly over large distances by generating characteristic electrical pulses called action potentials: voltage spikes that can travel down axons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Sensory neurons change their activities by firing sequences of action potentials in various temporal patterns, with the presence of external sensory stimuli, such as light, sound, taste, smell and touch.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Information about the stimulus is encoded in this pattern of action potentials and transmitted into and around the brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Beyond this, specialized neurons, such as those of the retina, can communicate more information through graded potentials.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] These differ from action potentials because information about the strength of a stimulus directly correlates with the strength of the neurons' output.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The signal decays much faster for graded potentials, necessitating short inter-neuron distances and high neuronal density.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The advantage of graded potentials is higher information rates capable of encoding more states (i.e. higher fidelity) than spiking neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Although action potentials can vary somewhat in duration, amplitude and shape, they are typically treated as identical stereotyped events in neural coding studies.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If the brief duration of an action potential (about 1 ms) is ignored, an action potential sequence, or spike train, can be characterized simply by a series of all-or-none point events in time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The lengths of interspike intervals (ISIs) between two successive spikes in a spike train often vary, apparently randomly.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The study of neural coding involves measuring and characterizing how stimulus attributes, such as light or sound intensity, or motor actions, such as the direction of an arm movement, are represented by neuron action potentials or spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In order to describe and analyze neuronal firing, statistical methods and methods of probability theory and stochastic point processes have been widely applied.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Neuroscientists have initiated several large-scale brain decoding projects.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The link between stimulus and response can be studied from two opposite points of view.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Neural encoding refers to the map from stimulus to response.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The main focus is to understand how neurons respond to a wide variety of stimuli, and to construct models that attempt to predict responses to other stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Neural decoding refers to the reverse map, from response to stimulus, and the challenge is to reconstruct a stimulus, or certain aspects of that stimulus, from the spike sequences it evokes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A sequence, or 'train', of spikes may contain information based on different coding schemes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In some neurons the strength with which a postsynaptic partner responds may depend solely on the 'firing rate', the average number of spikes per unit time (a 'rate code').
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] At the other end, a complex 'temporal code' is based on the precise timing of single spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] They may be locked to an external stimulus such as in the visual and auditory system or be generated intrinsically by the neural circuitry.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Whether neurons use rate coding or temporal coding is a topic of intense debate within the neuroscience community, even though there is no clear definition of what these terms mean.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The rate coding model of neuronal firing communication states that as the intensity of a stimulus increases, the frequency or rate of action potentials, or "spike firing", increases.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Rate coding is sometimes called frequency coding.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Rate coding is a traditional coding scheme, assuming that most, if not all, information about the stimulus is contained in the firing rate of the neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Because the sequence of action potentials generated by a given stimulus varies from trial to trial, neuronal responses are typically treated statistically or probabilistically.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] They may be characterized by firing rates, rather than as specific spike sequences.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In most sensory systems, the firing rate increases, generally non-linearly, with increasing stimulus intensity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Under a rate coding assumption, any information possibly encoded in the temporal structure of the spike train is ignored.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Consequently, rate coding is inefficient but highly robust with respect to the ISI 'noise'.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] During rate coding, precisely calculating firing rate is very important.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In fact, the term "firing rate" has a few different definitions, which refer to different averaging procedures, such as an **average over time** (rate as a single-neuron spike count) or an **average over several repetitions** (rate of PSTH) of experiment.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In rate coding, learning is based on activity-dependent synaptic weight modifications.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Rate coding was originally shown by Edgar Adrian and Yngve Zotterman in 1926.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In this simple experiment different weights were hung from a muscle.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As the weight of the stimulus increased, the number of spikes recorded from sensory nerves innervating the muscle also increased.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] From these original experiments, Adrian and Zotterman concluded that action potentials were unitary events, and that the frequency of events, and not individual event magnitude, was the basis for most inter-neuronal communication.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In the following decades, measurement of firing rates became a standard tool for describing the properties of all types of sensory or cortical neurons, partly due to the relative ease of measuring rates experimentally.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, this approach neglects all the information possibly contained in the exact timing of the spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] During recent years, more and more experimental evidence has suggested that a straightforward firing rate concept based on temporal averaging may be too simplistic to describe brain activity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The spike-count rate, also referred to as temporal average, is obtained by counting the number of spikes that appear during a trial and dividing by the duration of trial.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The length T of the time window is set by the experimenter and depends on the type of neuron recorded from and to the stimulus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In practice, to get sensible averages, several spikes should occur within the time window.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Typical values are T = 100 ms or T = 500 ms, but the duration may also be longer or shorter (Chapter 1.5 in the textbook 'Spiking Neuron Models' ).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The spike-count rate can be determined from a single trial, but at the expense of losing all temporal resolution about variations in neural response during the course of the trial.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Temporal averaging can work well in cases where the stimulus is constant or slowly varying and does not require a fast reaction of the organism — and this is the situation usually encountered in experimental protocols.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Real-world input, however, is hardly stationary, but often changing on a fast time scale.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For example, even when viewing a static image, humans perform saccades, rapid changes of the direction of gaze.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Despite its shortcomings, the concept of a spike-count rate code is widely used not only in experiments, but also in models of neural networks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] It has led to the idea that a neuron transforms information about a single input variable (the stimulus strength) into a single continuous output variable (the firing rate).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] There is a growing body of evidence that in Purkinje neurons, at least, information is not simply encoded in firing but also in the timing and duration of non-firing, quiescent periods.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] There is also evidence from retinal cells, that information is encoded not only in the firing rate but also in spike timing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] More generally, whenever a rapid response of an organism is required a firing rate defined as a spike-count over a few hundred milliseconds is simply too slow.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The time-dependent firing rate is defined as the average number of spikes (averaged over trials) appearing during a short interval between times t and t+Δt, divided by the duration of the interval.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] It works for stationary as well as for time-dependent stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] To experimentally measure the time-dependent firing rate, the experimenter records from a neuron while stimulating with some input sequence.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The same stimulation sequence is repeated several times and the neuronal response is reported in a Peri-Stimulus-Time Histogram (PSTH).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The time t is measured with respect to the start of the stimulation sequence.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The Δt must be large enough (typically in the range of one or a few milliseconds) so that there is a sufficient number of spikes within the interval to obtain a reliable estimate of the average.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The number of occurrences of spikes nK(t;t+Δt) summed over all repetitions of the experiment divided by the number K of repetitions is a measure of the typical activity of the neuron between time t and t+Δt.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A further division by the interval length Δt yields time-dependent firing rate r(t) of the neuron, which is equivalent to the spike density of PSTH (Chapter 1.5 in ).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For sufficiently small Δt, r(t)Δt is the average number of spikes occurring between times t and t+Δt over multiple trials.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If Δt is small, there will never be more than one spike within the interval between t and t+Δt on any given trial.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This means that r(t)Δt is also the fraction of trials on which a spike occurred between those times.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Equivalently, r(t)Δt is the probability that a spike occurs during this time interval.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As an experimental procedure, the time-dependent firing rate measure is a useful method to evaluate neuronal activity, in particular in the case of time-dependent stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The obvious problem with this approach is that it can not be the coding scheme used by neurons in the brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Neurons can not wait for the stimuli to repeatedly present in an exactly same manner before generating a response.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Nevertheless, the experimental time-dependent firing rate measure can make sense, if there are large populations of independent neurons that receive the same stimulus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Instead of recording from a population of N neurons in a single run, it is experimentally easier to record from a single neuron and average over N repeated runs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Thus, the time-dependent firing rate coding relies on the implicit assumption that there are always populations of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] When precise spike timing or high-frequency firing-rate fluctuations are found to carry information, the neural code is often identified as a temporal code.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A number of studies have found that the temporal resolution of the neural code is on a millisecond time scale, indicating that precise spike timing is a significant element in neural coding.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Such codes, that communicate via the time between spikes are also referred to as interpulse interval codes, and have been supported by recent studies.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Neurons exhibit high-frequency fluctuations of firing-rates which could be noise or could carry information.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Rate coding models suggest that these irregularities are noise, while temporal coding models suggest that they encode information.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If the nervous system only used rate codes to convey information, a more consistent, regular firing rate would have been evolutionarily advantageous, and neurons would have utilized this code over other less robust options.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Temporal coding supplies an alternate explanation for the "noise," suggesting that it actually encodes information and affects neural processing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] To model this idea, binary symbols can be used to mark the spikes: 1 for a spike, 0 for no spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Temporal coding allows the sequence 000111000111 to mean something different from 001100110011, even though the mean firing rate is the same for both sequences, at 6 spikes/10 ms.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Until recently, scientists had put the most emphasis on rate encoding as an explanation for post-synaptic potential patterns.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, functions of the brain are more temporally precise than the use of only rate encoding seems to allow.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In other words, essential information could be lost due to the inability of the rate code to capture all the available information of the spike train.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In addition, responses are different enough between similar (but not identical) stimuli to suggest that the distinct patterns of spikes contain a higher volume of information than is possible to include in a rate code.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Temporal codes (also called spike codes), employ those features of the spiking activity that cannot be described by the firing rate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As there is no absolute time reference in the nervous system, the information is carried either in terms of the relative timing of spikes in a population of neurons (temporal patterns) or with respect to an ongoing brain oscillation (phase of firing).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] One way in which temporal codes are decoded, in presence of neural oscillations, is that spikes occurring at specific phases of an oscillatory cycle are more effective in depolarizing the post-synaptic neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The temporal structure of a spike train or firing rate evoked by a stimulus is determined both by the dynamics of the stimulus and by the nature of the neural encoding process.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Stimuli that change rapidly tend to generate precisely timed spikes (and rapidly changing firing rates in PSTHs) no matter what neural coding strategy is being used.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Temporal coding in the narrow sense refers to temporal precision in the response that does not arise solely from the dynamics of the stimulus, but that nevertheless relates to properties of the stimulus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The interplay between stimulus and encoding dynamics makes the identification of a temporal code difficult.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In temporal coding, learning can be explained by activity-dependent synaptic delay modifications.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The modifications can themselves depend not only on spike rates (rate coding) but also on spike timing patterns (temporal coding), i.e., can be a special case of spike-timing-dependent plasticity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The issue of temporal coding is distinct and independent from the issue of independent-spike coding.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If each spike is independent of all the other spikes in the train, the temporal character of the neural code is determined by the behavior of time-dependent firing rate r(t).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If r(t) varies slowly with time, the code is typically called a rate code, and if it varies rapidly, the code is called temporal.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For very brief stimuli, a neuron's maximum firing rate may not be fast enough to produce more than a single spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Due to the density of information about the abbreviated stimulus contained in this single spike, it would seem that the timing of the spike itself would have to convey more information than simply the average frequency of action potentials over a given period of time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This model is especially important for sound localization, which occurs within the brain on the order of milliseconds.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The brain must obtain a large quantity of information based on a relatively short neural response.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Additionally, if low firing rates on the order of ten spikes per second must be distinguished from arbitrarily close rate coding for different stimuli, then a neuron trying to discriminate these two stimuli may need to wait for a second or more to accumulate enough information.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This is not consistent with numerous organisms which are able to discriminate between stimuli in the time frame of milliseconds, suggesting that a rate code is not the only model at work.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] To account for the fast encoding of visual stimuli, it has been suggested that neurons of the retina encode visual information in the latency time between stimulus onset and first action potential, also called latency to first spike or time-to-first-spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This type of temporal coding has been shown also in the auditory and somato-sensory system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The main drawback of such a coding scheme is its sensitivity to intrinsic neuronal fluctuations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In the primary visual cortex of macaques, the timing of the first spike relative to the start of the stimulus was found to provide more information than the interval between spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, the interspike interval could be used to encode additional information, which is especially important when the spike rate reaches its limit, as in high-contrast situations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For this reason, temporal coding may play a part in coding defined edges rather than gradual transitions.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The mammalian gustatory system is useful for studying temporal coding because of its fairly distinct stimuli and the easily discernible responses of the organism.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Temporally encoded information may help an organism discriminate between different tastants of the same category (sweet, bitter, sour, salty, umami) that elicit very similar responses in terms of spike count.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The temporal component of the pattern elicited by each tastant may be used to determine its identity (e.g., the difference between two bitter tastants, such as quinine and denatonium).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In this way, both rate coding and temporal coding may be used in the gustatory system – rate for basic tastant type, temporal for more specific differentiation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Research on mammalian gustatory system has shown that there is an abundance of information present in temporal patterns across populations of neurons, and this information is different from that which is determined by rate coding schemes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Groups of neurons may synchronize in response to a stimulus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In studies dealing with the front cortical portion of the brain in primates, precise patterns with short time scales only a few milliseconds in length were found across small populations of neurons which correlated with certain information processing behaviors.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, little information could be determined from the patterns; one possible theory is they represented the higher-order processing taking place in the brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As with the visual system, in mitral/tufted cells in the olfactory bulb of mice, first-spike latency relative to the start of a sniffing action seemed to encode much of the information about an odor.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This strategy of using spike latency allows for rapid identification of and reaction to an odorant.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In addition, some mitral/tufted cells have specific firing patterns for given odorants.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This type of extra information could help in recognizing a certain odor, but is not completely necessary, as average spike count over the course of the animal's sniffing was also a good identifier.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Along the same lines, experiments done with the olfactory system of rabbits showed distinct patterns which correlated with different subsets of odorants, and a similar result was obtained in experiments with the locust olfactory system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The specificity of temporal coding requires highly refined technology to measure informative, reliable, experimental data.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Advances made in optogenetics allow neurologists to control spikes in individual neurons, offering electrical and spatial single-cell resolution.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For example, blue light causes the light-gated ion channel channelrhodopsin to open, depolarizing the cell and producing a spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] When blue light is not sensed by the cell, the channel closes, and the neuron ceases to spike.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The pattern of the spikes matches the pattern of the blue light stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] By inserting channelrhodopsin gene sequences into mouse DNA, researchers can control spikes and therefore certain behaviors of the mouse (e.g., making the mouse turn left).
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Researchers, through optogenetics, have the tools to effect different temporal codes in a neuron while maintaining the same mean firing rate, and thereby can test whether or not temporal coding occurs in specific neural circuits.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Optogenetic technology also has the potential to enable the correction of spike abnormalities at the root of several neurological and psychological disorders.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If neurons do encode information in individual spike timing patterns, key signals could be missed by attempting to crack the code while looking only at mean firing rates.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Understanding any temporally encoded aspects of the neural code and replicating these sequences in neurons could allow for greater control and treatment of neurological disorders such as depression, schizophrenia, and Parkinson's disease.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Regulation of spike intervals in single cells more precisely controls brain activity than the addition of pharmacological agents intravenously.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Phase-of-firing code is a neural coding scheme that combines the spike count code with a time reference based on oscillations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This type of code takes into account a time label for each spike according to a time reference based on phase of local ongoing oscillations at low or high frequencies.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] It has been shown that neurons in some cortical sensory areas encode rich naturalistic stimuli in terms of their spike times relative to the phase of ongoing network oscillatory fluctuations, rather than only in terms of their spike count.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The local field potential signals reflect population (network) oscillations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The phase-of-firing code is often categorized as a temporal code although the time label used for spikes (i.e. the network oscillation phase) is a low-resolution (coarse-grained) reference for time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As a result, often only four discrete values for the phase are enough to represent all the information content in this kind of code with respect to the phase of oscillations in low frequencies.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Phase-of-firing code is loosely based on the phase precession phenomena observed in place cells of the hippocampus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Another feature of this code is that neurons adhere to a preferred order of spiking between a group of sensory neurons, resulting in firing sequence.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Phase code has been shown in visual cortex to involve also high-frequency oscillations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Within a cycle of gamma oscillation, each neuron has its own preferred relative firing time.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As a result, an entire population of neurons generates a firing sequence that has a duration of up to about 15 ms.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Population coding is a method to represent stimuli by using the joint activities of a number of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In population coding, each neuron has a distribution of responses over some set of inputs, and the responses of many neurons may be combined to determine some value about the inputs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] From the theoretical point of view, population coding is one of a few mathematically well-formulated problems in neuroscience.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] It grasps the essential features of neural coding and yet is simple enough for theoretic analysis.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Experimental studies have revealed that this coding paradigm is widely used in the sensory and motor areas of the brain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For example, in the visual area medial temporal (MT), neurons are tuned to the direction of object motion.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In response to an object moving in a particular direction, many neurons in MT fire with a noise-corrupted and bell-shaped activity pattern across the population.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The moving direction of the object is retrieved from the population activity, to be immune from the fluctuation existing in a single neuron's signal.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] When monkeys are trained to move a joystick towards a lit target, a single neuron will fire for multiple target directions.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However it fires the fastest for one direction and more slowly depending on how close the target was to the neuron's "preferred" direction.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If each neuron represents movement in its preferred direction, and the vector sum of all neurons is calculated (each neuron has a firing rate and a preferred direction), the sum points in the direction of motion.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In this manner, the population of neurons codes the signal for the motion.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This particular population code is referred to as population vector coding.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Place-time population codes, termed the averaged-localized-synchronized-response (ALSR) code, have been derived for neural representation of auditory acoustic stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This exploits both the place or tuning within the auditory nerve, as well as the phase-locking within each nerve fiber auditory nerve.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The first ALSR representation was for steady-state vowels; ALSR representations of pitch and formant frequencies in complex, non-steady state stimuli were later demonstrated for voiced-pitch, and formant representations in consonant-vowel syllables.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The advantage of such representations is that global features such as pitch or formant transition profiles can be represented as global features across the entire nerve simultaneously via both rate and place coding.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Population coding has a number of other advantages as well, including reduction of uncertainty due to neuronal variability and the ability to represent a number of different stimulus attributes simultaneously.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Population coding is also much faster than rate coding and can reflect changes in the stimulus conditions nearly instantaneously.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Individual neurons in such a population typically have different but overlapping selectivities, so that many neurons, but not necessarily all, respond to a given stimulus.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Typically an encoding function has a peak value such that activity of the neuron is greatest if the perceptual value is close to the peak value, and becomes reduced accordingly for values less close to the peak value.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] It follows that the actual perceived value can be reconstructed from the overall pattern of activity in the set of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Vector coding is an example of simple averaging.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A more sophisticated mathematical technique for performing such a reconstruction is the method of maximum likelihood based on a multivariate distribution of the neuronal responses.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] These models can assume independence, second order correlations, or even more detailed dependencies such as higher order maximum entropy models, or copulas.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The correlation coding model of neuronal firing claims that correlations between action potentials, or "spikes", within a spike train may carry additional information above and beyond the simple timing of the spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Early work suggested that correlation between spike trains can only reduce, and never increase, the total mutual information present in the two spike trains about a stimulus feature.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, this was later demonstrated to be incorrect.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Correlation structure can increase information content if noise and signal correlations are of opposite sign.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Correlations can also carry information not present in the average firing rate of two pairs of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A good example of this exists in the pentobarbital-anesthetized marmoset auditory cortex, in which a pure tone causes an increase in the number of correlated spikes, but not an increase in the mean firing rate, of pairs of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The independent-spike coding model of neuronal firing claims that each individual action potential, or "spike", is independent of each other spike within the spike train.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A typical population code involves neurons with a Gaussian tuning curve whose means vary linearly with the stimulus intensity, meaning that the neuron responds most strongly (in terms of spikes per second) to a stimulus near the mean.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The actual intensity could be recovered as the stimulus level corresponding to the mean of the neuron with the greatest response.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, the noise inherent in neural responses means that a maximum likelihood estimation function is more accurate.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This type of code is used to encode continuous variables such as joint position, eye position, color, or sound frequency.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Any individual neuron is too noisy to faithfully encode the variable using rate coding, but an entire population ensures greater fidelity and precision.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For a population of unimodal tuning curves, i.e. with a single peak, the precision typically scales linearly with the number of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Hence, for half the precision, half as many neurons are required.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In contrast, when the tuning curves have multiple peaks, as in grid cells that represent space, the precision of the population can scale exponentially with the number of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This greatly reduces the number of neurons required for the same precision.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Dimensionality reduction and topological data analysis, have revealed that the population code is constrained to low-dimensional manifolds, sometimes also referred to as attractors.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The low-dimensional manifolds are known to change in a state dependent manner, such as eye closure in the visual cortex, or breathing behavior in the ventral respiratory column.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The sparse code is when each item is encoded by the strong activation of a relatively small set of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For each item to be encoded, this is a different subset of all available neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In contrast to sensor-sparse coding, sensor-dense coding implies that all information from possible sensor locations is known.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] As a consequence, sparseness may be focused on temporal sparseness ("a relatively small number of time periods are active") or on the sparseness in an activated population of neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In this latter case, this may be defined in one time period as the number of activated neurons relative to the total number of neurons in the population.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This seems to be a hallmark of neural computations since compared to traditional computers, information is massively distributed across neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Sparse coding of natural images produces wavelet-like oriented filters that resemble the receptive fields of simple cells in the visual cortex.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The capacity of sparse codes may be increased by simultaneous use of temporal coding, as found in the locust olfactory system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Given a potentially large set of input patterns, sparse coding algorithms (e.g. sparse autoencoder) attempt to automatically find a small number of representative patterns which, when combined in the right proportions, reproduce the original input patterns.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The sparse coding for the input then consists of those representative patterns.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] For example, the very large set of English sentences can be encoded by a small number of symbols (i.e. letters, numbers, punctuation, and spaces) combined in a particular order for a particular sentence, and so a sparse coding for English would be those symbols.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Most models of sparse coding are based on the linear generative model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In this model, the symbols are combined in a linear fashion to approximate the input.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The codings generated by algorithms implementing a linear generative model can be classified into codings with *soft sparseness* and those with *hard sparseness*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] These refer to the distribution of basis vector coefficients for typical inputs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] A coding with soft sparseness has a smooth Gaussian-like distribution, but peakier than Gaussian, with many zero values, some small absolute values, fewer larger absolute values, and very few very large absolute values.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Thus, many of the basis vectors are active.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Hard sparseness, on the other hand, indicates that there are many zero values, *no* or *hardly any* small absolute values, fewer larger absolute values, and very few very large absolute values, and thus few of the basis vectors are active.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] This is appealing from a metabolic perspective: less energy is used when fewer neurons are firing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Another measure of coding is whether it is *critically complete* or *overcomplete*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If the number of basis vectors n is equal to the dimensionality k of the input set, the coding is said to be critically complete.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In this case, smooth changes in the input vector result in abrupt changes in the coefficients, and the coding is not able to gracefully handle small scalings, small translations, or noise in the inputs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] If, however, the number of basis vectors is larger than the dimensionality of the input set, the coding is *overcomplete*.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Overcomplete codings smoothly interpolate between input vectors and are robust under input noise.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] The human primary visual cortex is estimated to be overcomplete by a factor of 500, so that, for example, a 14 x 14 patch of input (a 196-dimensional space) is coded by roughly 100,000 neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Sparse coding may be a general strategy of neural systems to augment memory capacity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] To adapt to their environments, animals must learn which stimuli are associated with rewards or punishments and distinguish these reinforced stimuli from similar but irrelevant ones.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Such tasks require implementing stimulus-specific associative memories in which only a few neurons out of a population respond to any given stimulus and each neuron responds to only a few stimuli out of all possible stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Theoretical work on sparse distributed memory has suggested that sparse coding increases the capacity of associative memory by reducing overlap between representations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Experimentally, sparse representations of sensory information have been observed in many systems, including vision, audition, touch, and olfaction.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] However, despite the accumulating evidence for widespread sparse coding and theoretical arguments for its importance, a demonstration that sparse coding improves the stimulus-specificity of associative memory has been difficult to obtain.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] In the *Drosophila* olfactory system, sparse odor coding by the Kenyon cells of the mushroom body is thought to generate a large number of precisely addressable locations for the storage of odor-specific memories.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Sparseness is controlled by a negative feedback circuit between Kenyon cells and GABAergic anterior paired lateral (APL) neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Systematic activation and blockade of each leg of this feedback circuit shows that Kenyon cells activate APL neurons and APL neurons inhibit Kenyon cells.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] Disrupting the Kenyon cell–APL feedback loop decreases the sparseness of Kenyon cell odor responses, increases inter-odor correlations, and prevents flies from learning to discriminate similar, but not dissimilar, odors.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neural-coding] These results suggest that feedback inhibition suppresses Kenyon cell activity to maintain sparse, decorrelated odor coding and thus the odor-specificity of memories.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Single neurons demonstrate different responses to specific neuronal input signals.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] This is commonly referred to as neural response variability.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] If a specific input signal is initiated in the dendrites of a neuron, then a hypervariability exists in the number of vesicles released from the axon terminal fiber into the synapse.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] This characteristic is true for fibers without neural input signals, such as pacemaker neurons, as mentioned previously, and cortical pyramidal neurons that have highly-irregular firing pattern.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Noise generally hinders neural performance, but recent studies show, in dynamical non-linear neural networks, this statement does not always hold true.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Non-linear neural networks are a network of complex neurons that have many connections with one another such as the neuronal systems found within our brains.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Comparatively, linear networks are an experimental view of analyzing a neural system by placing neurons in series with each other.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Initially, noise in complex computer circuit or neural circuits is thought to slow down and negatively affect the processing power.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] However, current research suggests that neuronal noise is beneficial to non-linear or complex neural networks up until optimal value.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] A theory by Anderson and colleagues supports that neural noise is beneficial.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Their theory suggests that noise produced in the visual cortex helps linearize or smooth the threshold of action potentials.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Another theory suggests that stochastic noise in a non-linear network shows a positive relationship between the interconnectivity and noise-like activity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Thus based on this theory, Patrick Wilken and colleagues suggest that neuronal noise is the principal factor that limits the capacity of visual short-term memory.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Investigators of neural ensembles and those who especially support the theory of distributed processing, propose that large neuronal populations effectively decrease noise by averaging out the noise in individual neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] Some investigators have shown in experiments and in models that neuronal noise is a possible mechanism to facilitate neuronal processing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] The presence of neuronal noise (or more specifically synaptic noise) confers to neurons more sensitivity to a broader range of inputs, it can equalize the efficacy of synaptic inputs located at different positions on the neuron, and it can also enable finer temporal discrimination.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] There are many theories of why noise is apparent in the neuronal networks, but many neurologists are unclear of why they exist.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] More generally, two types of impacts of neuronal noise can be distinguished: it will either add variability to the neural response, or enable noise-induced dynamical phenomena which cannot be observed in a noise-free system.
[src:computational-neuroscience/neuronal-noise] For instance, channel noise has been shown to induce oscillations in the stochastic Hodgkin-Huxley model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] In addition to neuronal and synaptic state, SNNs incorporate the concept of time into their operating model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] When the membrane potential reaches the threshold, the neuron fires, and generates a signal that travels to other neurons which, in turn, increase or decrease their potentials in response to this signal.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] A neuron model that fires at the moment of threshold crossing is also called a spiking neuron model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] While spike rates can be considered the analogue of the variable output of a traditional ANN, neurobiology research indicated that high speed processing cannot be performed solely through a rate-based scheme.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] For example humans can perform an image recognition task requiring no more than 10ms of processing time per neuron through the successive layers (going from the retina to the temporal lobe).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This time window is too short for rate-based encoding.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The precise spike timings in a small set of spiking neurons also has a higher information coding capacity compared with a rate-based approach.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The most prominent spiking neuron model is the leaky integrate-and-fire model.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] In that model, the momentary activation level (modeled as a differential equation) is normally considered to be the neuron's state, with incoming spikes pushing this value higher or lower, until the state eventually either decays or—if the firing threshold is reached—the neuron fires.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] After firing, the state variable is reset to a lower value.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Various decoding methods exist for interpreting the outgoing *spike train* as a real-value number, relying on either the frequency of spikes (rate-code), the time-to-first-spike after stimulation, or the interval between spikes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Many multi-layer artificial neural networks are fully connected, receiving input from every neuron in the previous layer and signalling every neuron in the subsequent layer.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Although these networks have achieved breakthroughs, they do not match biological networks and do not mimic neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The biology-inspired Hodgkin–Huxley model of a spiking neuron was proposed in 1952.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This model described how action potentials are initiated and propagated.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Communication between neurons, which requires the exchange of chemical neurotransmitters in the synaptic gap, is described in models such as the integrate-and-fire model, FitzHugh–Nagumo model (1961–1962), and Hindmarsh–Rose model (1984).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The leaky integrate-and-fire model (or a derivative) is commonly used as it is easier to compute than Hodgkin–Huxley.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] While the notion of an artificial spiking neural network became popular only in the twenty-first century, studies between 1980 and 1995 supported the concept.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The first models of this type of ANN appeared to simulate non-algorithmic intelligent information processing systems.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] However, the notion of the spiking neural network as a mathematical model was first worked on in the early 1970s.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] As of 2019 SNNs lagged behind ANNs in accuracy, but the gap is decreasing, and has vanished on some tasks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Information in the brain is represented as action potentials (neuron spikes), which may group into spike trains or coordinated waves.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] A fundamental question of neuroscience is to determine whether neurons communicate by a rate or temporal code.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] SNNs define a neuron's current state as its potential (possibly modeled as a differential equation).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] An input pulse causes the potential to rise and then gradually decline.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Encoding schemes can interpret these pulse sequences as a number, considering pulse frequency and pulse interval.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Using the precise time of pulse occurrence, a neural network can consider more information and offer better computing properties.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Such neurons test for activation only when their potentials reach a certain value.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] When a neuron is activated, it produces a signal that is passed to connected neurons, accordingly raising or lowering their potentials.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The SNN approach produces a continuous output instead of the binary output of traditional ANNs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Pulse trains are not easily interpretable, hence the need for encoding schemes.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] However, a pulse train representation may be more suited for processing spatiotemporal data (or real-world sensory data classification).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] SNNs connect neurons only to nearby neurons so that they process input blocks separately (similar to CNN using filters).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] They consider time by encoding information as pulse trains so as not to lose information.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This avoids the complexity of a recurrent neural network (RNN).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Impulse neurons are more powerful computational units than traditional artificial neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Although unsupervised biologically inspired learning methods are available such as Hebbian learning and STDP, no effective supervised training method is suitable for SNNs that can provide better performance than second-generation networks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Spike-based activation of SNNs is not differentiable, thus gradient descent-based backpropagation (BP) is not available.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] SNNs have much larger computational costs for simulating realistic neural models than traditional ANNs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Pulse-coupled neural networks (PCNN) are often confused with SNNs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Researchers are actively working on various topics.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The expressions for both the forward- and backward-learning methods contain the derivative of the neural activation function which is not differentiable because a neuron's output is either 1 when it spikes, and 0 otherwise.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This all-or-nothing behavior disrupts gradients and makes these neurons unsuitable for gradient-based optimization.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The second concerns the optimization algorithm.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Standard BP can be expensive in terms of computation, memory, and communication and may be poorly suited to the hardware that implements it (e.g., a computer, brain, or neuromorphic device).
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Incorporating additional neuron dynamics such as Spike Frequency Adaptation (SFA) is a notable advance, enhancing efficiency and computational power.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] These neurons sit between biological complexity and computational complexity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Originating from biological insights, SFA offers significant computational benefits by reducing power usage, especially in cases of repetitive or intense stimuli.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This adaptation improves signal/noise clarity and introduces an elementary short-term memory at the neuron level, which in turn, improves accuracy and efficiency.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This was mostly achieved using compartmental neuron models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] The simpler versions are of neuron models with adaptive thresholds, are an indirect way of achieving SFA.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] It equips SNNs with improved learning capabilities, even with constrained synaptic plasticity, and elevates computational efficiency.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This feature lessens the demand on network layers by decreasing the need for spike processing, thus lowering computational load and memory access time—essential aspects of neural computation.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Moreover, SNNs utilizing neurons capable of SFA achieve levels of accuracy that rival those of conventional ANNs, while also requiring fewer neurons for comparable tasks.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] This efficiency streamlines the computational workflow and conserves space and energy, while maintaining technical integrity.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] High-performance deep spiking neural networks can operate with 0.3 spikes per neuron.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] SNNs can in principle be applied to the same applications as traditional ANNs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] In addition, SNNs can model the central nervous system of biological organisms, such as an insect seeking food without prior knowledge of the environment.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Due to their relative realism, they can be used to study biological neural circuits.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Starting with a hypothesis about the topology of a biological neuronal circuit and its function, recordings of this circuit can be compared to the output of a corresponding SNN, evaluating the plausibility of the hypothesis.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] SNNs lack effective training mechanisms, which can complicate some applications, including computer vision.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] When using SNNs for image based data, the images need to be converted into binary spike trains.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] A diverse range of application software can simulate SNNs.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Large networks usually require lengthy processing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Efforts to implement hardware-based spiking neural networks (SNNs) began in the 1980s, when researchers began exploring brain-inspired neuromorphic systems.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] In the following decades, advancements in semiconductor technologies enabled the development of several notable projects.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] One such project is SpiNNaker, developed at the University of Manchester, which utilizes millions of processing cores for large-scale simulation of spiking neurons.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] TrueNorth, developed by IBM, is one of the first commercial neuromorphic chips, designed for energy-efficient and parallel processing.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Loihi, an Intel research chip, focuses on online learning and adaptability in neuromorphic modeling.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] In research contexts, platforms such as BrainScaleS, developed in Europe, integrate analog and digital circuitry to accelerate neural simulations.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Neurogrid, from Stanford University, was designed to efficiently simulate biological neurons and synapses.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Dynap-se models developed by iniLabs, are a family of low-power, event-based neuromorphic chip intended for use in robotics and Internet of Things (IoT) applications.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] In addition, hardware based on memristors and other emerging memory technologies is being explored for the implementation of SNNs, with the goal of achieving lower power consumption and improved compatibility with biological neural models.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Sutton and Barto proposed that future neuromorphic architectures will comprise billions of nanosynapses, which require a clear understanding of the accompanying physical mechanisms.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Experimental systems based on ferroelectric tunnel junctions have been used to show that STDP can be harnessed from heterogeneous polarization switching.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Through combined scanning probe imaging, electrical transport and atomic-scale molecular dynamics, conductance variations can be modelled by nucleation-dominated domain reversal.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Simulations showed that arrays of ferroelectric nanosynapses can autonomously learn to recognize patterns in a predictable way, opening the path towards unsupervised learning.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Classification capabilities of spiking networks trained according to unsupervised learning methods have been tested on benchmark datasets such as Iris, Wisconsin Breast Cancer or Statlog Landsat dataset.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Various approaches to information encoding and network design have been used such as a 2-layer feedforward network for data clustering and classification.
[src:computational-neuroscience/spiking-neural-network] Based on Hopfield (1995) the authors implemented models of local receptive fields combining the properties of radial basis functions and spiking neurons to convert input signals having a floating-point representation into a spiking representation.
